using UnityEngine;

public class Enemy
{
    public string name;

    // Forgot a constructor entirely!
    // C# will provide a default one with no parameters.
    // But you still need to initialize fields properly.
}

public class ConstructorError : MonoBehaviour
{
    void Start()
    {
        Enemy e = new Enemy();
        Debug.Log(e.name);  // name is null!
    }
}

phase2.explanation:
If you don't provide a constructor, C# gives you a default one — but it doesn't initialize your fields to meaningful values.

**The fix:**
```csharp
public class Enemy
{
    public string name;

    // Add a constructor
    public Enemy()
    {
        name = "Unknown Enemy";
    }
}
```

**Sharp-chan says:**
"Always write constructors to initialize your fields. Don't rely on C# to handle it for you."
